comment:
Commentary aside, looking at it objectively, she is referring to the fact that he, Johnny Depp, not he, a man, has never been overpowered by her. And people keep making this 'reverse sexism' thing over it.
They are both, at the end, acting very normal for people who are breaking up. And I will call anyone who's been in three breakups or more a liar for claiming they've never acted exactly like both of them at one point. Be it an argument, or the actual breakup.
I'm sorry I disagree with the ongoing sentiment. I don't believe any one gender should be awarded special attention, and I don't believe either career should be tarnished by what is their love lives. This isn't like making a huge scandal and making someone completely blacklisted claiming they molested you, just to eventually admit that it was an at the time mutual kiss. This is just a breakup, overly publicised with unnecessary consequences. And people basically feeling, "If you want me to take this MeToo thing seriously, punish her," when it is really something they do not at all wish to take seriously. And that opinion is their business. But since I don't find enough coherent thought to this topic, I thought I'd chime for what might be misinterpreted as the opposition. Just to say, "No. Not everyone feels this way. And not everyone who disagrees is just, girlz rool boyz drool."
author: Pahlavan Habib

comment: Don't know much about this case, and is there really a need to. Millions of people have the same problems, OK a couple are in a loving and caring relationship for a period of time. As this time extends problems arise, could be countless reasons, but for the average couple its generally that there both working hard whilst trying to have a great relationship, not to mention financial difficulty's. Then there's all the mums and dads that either work or not, and are trying to balance their relationships. Regarding verbal abuse well is a common occurrence, I think it would be fair to say that men generally are seen to be the offenders. When a conversation takes place with a friend or even an acquaintance and this subject comes up there is generally little doubt that its not the man's fault that a failing relationship is happening. Looking at relationships that involve children become even more complicated, but that's another story. The main point here is that these 2 people I don't believe have children ? also they both are financially stable, so why did either of them continue the relationship ! why not simply end it when serious problems began to arise. They both had choices and easy outs, but it appears that they preferred to settle for a destructive lifestyle. Lastly constant verbal abuse over many years from your partner does certainty play havoc with your everyday affairs. Bottom line is nip it in the bud quickly or simply move on.

comment:
I personally never believed that Depp abused her. Usually, abusers have patterns. They don't often start up much later. If he was an abuser then his previous relationships would have shown some sign of it. So when this came out, I was pretty floored but didn't believe an ounce of it. I was more shocked that people believed her without much proof. Then when her picture went out with that injured eye, I was more than sure it looked faked. A lot of people disregarded me when I'd stick up for Depp because they all knew how much of a fan I am of his. 

All that being said, I'm glad that the real truth is coming out and all evidence shows that the proclaimed abuser has in fact been the abused. I hope that with all of this coming out and still coming that justice will rightfully be served and she is given the treatment many were quick to give Johnny before facts were proven. I also know that this is unlikely, but I hope that many will apologize for Johnny and stop punishing him for allegations that he didn't  commit. He doesn't deserve the backhand treatment he's been getting.
